english:
  title: Record of the Hall of Reverent Respect
  author: Kim Dun
  language: eng
  text: "Since ancient times, when sage rulers establish governance and accomplish their tasks, they must first clarify the calendar and teach the people the proper seasons for their labors. The essence of teaching the seasons lies in observing heaven and studying the celestial signs—this is why the celestial sphere and measuring instruments were created. Yet the methods of verification are so exquisitely precise that no single instrument or image can perfect them alone. Our sovereign lord therefore commanded the craftsmen to construct all manner of instruments and celestial devices: the great and small simplified armillaries, the universal sphere, the celestial globe, the inverted bowl sundial, the instruments for fixing the positions of sun and stars, the gnomon and water-clocks, and other devices. All possess exquisite craftsmanship, surpassing the designs of antiquity. Yet fearing that these provisions remained incomplete, and noting that all these instruments stood in the rear garden where timely observation was difficult, His Majesty commanded the construction of a small pavilion in the western courtyard of the Hall of Ten Thousand Autumns.\n\nPaper was applied to frame a mountain, raised to a height of seven feet, and placed within this hall. Within it, a jade mechanism of water-wheels was installed, driven by flowing water. A sun of gold, no larger than a projectile, travels along the mountain's slope, encircled by five-colored clouds, completing one revolution in a day. By daylight it appears beyond the mountain; at night it vanishes within. Following the oblique path of heaven's motion, it marks the distances from the celestial pole and the cycles of appearance and disappearance, each shifting with the seasons in perfect accord with heaven's own sun.\n\nBeneath the sun stand four jade maidens, each holding golden bells, mounted upon clouds at the four directions. When the early hours of Tiger, Hare, and Dragon arrive, the maiden to the east rings her bell; at the early hours of Snake, Horse, and Sheep, the southern maiden rings hers; the western and northern maidens do likewise. Below these, four divine protectors stand at their appointed directions, each facing the mountain. When the Hour of the Tiger comes, the Azure Dragon turns northward; at the Hour of the Hare, eastward; at the Hour of the Dragon, southward; at the Hour of the Snake, it turns westward again, while the Vermillion Bird returns to face east. Each continues in its appointed direction as before, and the others follow similarly.\n\nUpon the southern slope of the mountain stands a high platform. Here stands the Master of Hours, clad in crimson official robes, facing away from the mountain. Three warriors in full armor stand beside him: one holds a mallet and faces westward from the east; one holds a drumstick and faces eastward from the west, positioned toward the north; one holds a gong-beater and also faces eastward from the west, positioned toward the south. When each hour arrives, the Master of Hours turns to observe the gong-striker, and the gong-striker observes the Master in return, then strikes the gong. At each watch-change, the drummer strikes his drum; at each point of time, the gong-striker sounds the gong. Their mutual observation follows the same pattern, and the number of drum-beats and gong-sounds correspond to standard astronomical practice.\n\nBelow this, upon the ground, twelve divine beings crouch at their appointed positions. Behind each of these twelve stations lies a door, always sealed. When the Hour of the Rat arrives, the door behind the Rat opens of its own accord, a jade maiden emerges bearing a placard of the hour, and the rat figure rises before it. When the Hour of the Rat concludes, the maiden withdraws, the door seals itself, and the rat returns to its resting position. This pattern repeats for all twelve hours, with each animal emerging and retiring in turn.\n\nBefore the position of the Horse stands another platform, upon which rests a tilting vessel. To its north stands an official holding a golden ewer, pouring forth the overflow from the water-clock in an endless stream. When empty, the vessel tilts; when half-filled, it stands upright; when full, it overturns—all according to the ancient principles.\n\nOn the eastern slope of the mountain, the landscape of spring's three months appears; on the southern slope, that of summer's three months; autumn and winter are rendered likewise. Following the diagrams from the \"Hymns of Bin,\" wooden figures are carved in the forms of people, beasts, birds, and plants, arranged according to their seasonal appearance. All the scenes and activities described in the seventh month's verses are represented without omission.\n\nThe pavilion was named the \"Hall of Reverent Respect,\" taking its meaning from the Records of Yao: \"to reverently receive heaven's will and teach the people the proper seasons for their labors.\" From the age of the ancient sage-kings, instruments for celestial observation have been crafted in each era with different designs. Since the Tang and Song dynasties, their methods grew increasingly complete—the Tang possessed the celestial ecliptic, the wandering sphere, the water-driven mechanism, and the celestial globe; the Song had the floating clepsydra, the shadow-measuring instrument, and the armillary sphere with its moving model of the heavens; the Yuan possessed the inverted sphere and the simplified armillary. All were renowned for their ingenuity. Yet in general, each represented a single system only, without the integration of multiple instruments; and their operation relied heavily upon human manipulation.\n\nNow, however, the degrees of the heavens and sun, the markings upon the sundial and clepsydra, and all the mechanisms of the four divine protectors, the twelve animal signs, the drummer, the gong-striker, the Master of Hours, and the jade maidens move together in sequence without requiring human effort. They strike and move of their own accord, as though guided by spirits. Observers are struck with wonder, unable to discern the method. Yet in all their movements, they accord with the heavens' own course without the slightest deviation. Truly, the craftsmanship may be called sublime.\n\nMoreover, the overflow from the water-clock is channeled into the tilting vessel, where one may observe the principles of heaven's waxing and waning. The four sides of the mountain display scenes from the \"Hymns of Bin,\" revealing the laborious toil of the common people in their agricultural endeavors—innovations unknown to previous ages. Thus this pavilion constantly brings these lessons before the imperial gaze, ever stirring the royal heart to mindfulness, while embodying the virtue of ceaseless concern and diligent vigilance day and night. How can it compare merely to the washing-bowl of the ancient sage-king Tang or the inscribed warnings upon the gates of King Wu of Zhou? \n\nThe intention to follow heaven, accord with the seasons, and show reverence has been brought to its utmost perfection. The benevolence shown to the people and the reverence given to agriculture shall surely stand alongside the virtues of the Zhou dynasty and be transmitted through countless ages. Now that the pavilion stands complete, His Majesty has commanded this servant to record its creation. With utmost reverence, I respectfully present this account."
  footnotes:
    - The "Hymns of Bin" (豳風) refer to the seventh month of the Classic of Poetry, which depicts the agricultural cycle and seasonal labors of the common people.
    - The twelve animal signs mentioned correspond to the traditional Chinese zodiac system used for marking the twelve hours of the day and the twelve months of the year.
    - References to Tang (成湯), King Wu of Zhou (周武王), and their moral exemplars (the washing-bowl and gate inscriptions) invoke the Confucian tradition of rulers using objects as moral reminders of their duties.
